Design a rigorous methodology for calibrating the severity tiers of a code quality tool — specifically, how to decide which violations are blockers, which are major, which are minor, and which are informational. This calibration determines whether developers take the tool seriously or learn to ignore it.

The naive approach is to use expert opinion: senior engineers decide that cyclomatic complexity above 20 is a blocker and above 10 is a warning. But this leads to poorly-calibrated systems where the blocker tier fires constantly (leading to fatigue) or rarely (leading to under-investment in quality). Reason through a data-driven calibration approach. First, what empirical data would you need to calibrate severity tiers? Options include: the historical defect rate of code with each metric value from open-source projects (e.g., functions with cyclomatic complexity above 15 have 3x the defect rate of those below 5), the time developers actually spend fixing code with various metric values, and the frequency distribution of each metric value across open-source codebases of similar size and domain. Second, given such data, how would you set tier boundaries: at fixed percentiles (top 5% of all functions by complexity are blockers), at empirically derived defect-rate inflection points, or at values where developer remediation cost drops below some threshold? Third, how should severity tiers interact with code age and change frequency: should a function with cyclomatic complexity of 25 be downgraded from blocker to major if it has not been touched in two years and has zero recent changes? Fourth, how should severity tiers be communicated to be actionable rather than judgmental? Is "blocker" the right word, or should the tool use "fix before release", "fix this sprint", "fix when touching this file", and "fix in backlog"? Reason through the psychology of developer response to severity labels.
